social_posts.post_text: Polishing the foot and taking off powder from grinding some rough spots on this piece. Over the years, I have noticed that leaving silicon carbide grit or diamond grit in the crevices of a refired pot might lead to the glaze bubbling. I think the off gassing of the carbon gets trapped in the new layer of glaze. Now I will heat it to 180 F., spray another coat of white glaze and refire. I love the light bouncing off my new Day-Glo apron. #stoneware. #refire #wip #randcompany #edwardcellagallery #robishongallery @randcompanynyc @edwardcellagallery @robischongallery #venicebeach

Six weeks ago I posted the drying process for these very thick English porcelain bowls of which three of them cracked during the drying even after three or four weeks of carefully monitoring their dryness. Three more cracked in the bisque like this one.  The bisque was 34 hours. Very slow getting to red heat. This piece started out as a 12 pound ball of clay! Still 8 pounds after carving and going through a bisque fire.  Trapped carbon can lead to bloating because of being trapped in the clay and off gassing creating blisters.  Because I don’t see carbon in this this piece doesn’t mean it’s not there and might show up after high fire. I will put some of these in a high fire to see if they’re are truly free of carbon. #porcelain #wip #venicebeach

CURAUMILLA ART CENTER, CHILE,1/4 to 1/18, 2023
Pelusa Rosenthal has created an amazing ceramic center perched on a rocky cliff overlooking the Pacific Ocean west of Santiago. Pelusa began her career in ceramics in Chile and along the way found herself working on and off for six years with Doug Casebeer at the Anderson Ranch Arts Center,  in Snowmass, Colorado. Pelusa gained a tremendous amount of knowledge about ceramics, workshops and residencies.  Thirteen years ago she took that experience to Chile and started to envision and then construct Curaumilla. The facility is at the end of a dirt road and is totally off the grid.  Water is trucked in, fuel for firing is either wood or diesel and electricity is made by solar panels and a generator.  We all gathered around three extraordinary meals each day!

After shutting the facility during covid Pelusa reopened Curaumilla by gathered a group of potters to spend two weeks at Curaumilla. Doug Casebeer and David Pinto were the instructors.  There were 21  highly motivated and accomplished participants invited to attend the workshop plus 7 additional artists, including myself, were invited to work along side the group. The group was about 1/3 Chilean, 1/3 Basilian and 1/3 from the United States plus David Pinto from Jamaica. 

This was a mashup of dedicated participants from previous workshops and there were nine of us that had a range of experiences in employment at Anderson Ranch. The mix of overlapping threads of connectivity created a very rich and memorable tapestry.
The Milky Way was clearly visible each night. Orion was upside down from my normal view in Los Angeles.
Thank you Pelusa for creating such remarkable and memorable experience for us all!
#curaumillaartcenter  #pelusarosenthal

“Briliant Earth: The Ceramic Sculpture of Tony Marsh”  is entering the last three weeks of the exhibition which ends March 19th.  The  exhibition at the Long Beach Museum of Art  has more than 50 of Tony’s works  spanning 50 years, from 1972 to the present. The show is stunning and not to be missed. Tony has continually pushed his work into new and unexpected explorations.This video starts with the most recent pieces and moves back in time to his earliest works.
There is a beautifully published catalog for this exhibition and an in depth interview with Tony you can see on YouTube. Go!!!!!! #tonymarsh

Breaking the Rules to Fit Your Ideas with The Godfather himself: @bradmillerstudio

In this workshop, students explore a wide range of techniques for functional and sculptural pieces, developed over four decades of experimentation. Demonstrations and lectures focus on methods of altering clay bodies by using a broad array of additives, mixing and layering, and radical manipulation techniques for wet clay surfaces. Post-fire surface treatments including grinding and polishing techniques are discussed and demonstrated. Students learn new and unusual techniques that complement and greatly expand their ceramic repertoire.

Brenda Lee recorded “Rockin Around the Christmas Tree” in 1958 when she was 13 years old. She went on to have a massive career and is today 78 years old.  The way I scored, slipped, glazed, ground and polished this surface is one of my favorite results. #wintersolstice #brendalee #venicebeach

This ceramic rock is primarily made from a collection of bone dry pea sized chunks from making the carved bowls.  A very wet slurry of various materials including kaolin, vanadium, pentoxide, feldspar  and cone five leftover glazes was poured over the bone dry material and without being disturbed was slowly dried to a workable plastic consistency then formed into  this  shape. It will be fire to cone 10 then tumble gently to polish the surface without completely taking away the rough  surface. #venicebeach #stoneware
